WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:03.740
What's new in accessibility at Google?

2
00:00:05.260 --> 00:00:07.860
Hi everyone, it's Laura Allen again, Head of

3
00:00:07.860 --> 00:00:10.860
Strategy and Programs for Accessibility and Disability Inclusion

4
00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:11.320
here at Google.

5
00:00:11.980 --> 00:00:14.260
Welcome back to another episode of What's New

6
00:00:14.260 --> 00:00:16.760
in Google Accessibility, a series where we share

7
00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:18.760
new ways that we're making our products and

8
00:00:18.760 --> 00:00:20.820
features more accessible for everyone.

9
00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:23.800
In this episode, we'll talk about accessibility updates

10
00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:27.200
coming to products like Chrome OS, Android, Workspace,

11
00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:27.720
and more.

12
00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:30.260
So let's jump into it, starting with text

13
00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:31.360
-to-speech in Chrome OS.

14
00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:37.320
Earlier this year, we added new, more natural

15
00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:39.580
-sounding text-to-speech voices to Chrome OS,

16
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:41.860
so people now have a variety of different

17
00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:43.680
voices and languages to choose from.

18
00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:50.560
Text-to-speech allows users to hear text

19
00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:51.720
on their screen read aloud.

20
00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:54.560
This functionality can be helpful for individuals who

21
00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:57.140
have visual impairments, like me, or those who

22
00:00:57.140 --> 00:00:59.240
prefer to listen to content rather than read

23
00:00:59.240 --> 00:00:59.400
it.

24
00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:01.780
The new voice options can be used with

25
00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:04.760
ChromeVox, Chromebook's built-in screen reader, as well

26
00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:07.040
as select-to-speak, which allows for desired

27
00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:08.720
portions of pages to be read aloud.

28
00:01:11.970 --> 00:01:14.070
In Android news, we have a few exciting

29
00:01:14.070 --> 00:01:14.530
updates.

30
00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:17.970
First, we created a video tutorial series that

31
00:01:17.970 --> 00:01:20.210
offers tips for how to leverage some of

32
00:01:20.210 --> 00:01:23.310
our accessibility features and personalize your Android device

33
00:01:23.310 --> 00:01:24.450
based on your disability.

34
00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:27.670
For example, here's a clip from our video

35
00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:30.630
How to Navigate Your Phone Using Facial Gestures.

36
00:01:30.910 --> 00:01:33.290
We take a look at Camera Switches and

37
00:01:33.290 --> 00:01:36.310
Project Activate, two features that can help people

38
00:01:36.310 --> 00:01:38.550
use their phones through eye movements and facial

39
00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:38.950
gestures.

40
00:01:39.770 --> 00:01:42.390
Also in Android news, we've made some major

41
00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:44.810
updates to Lookout, our app that uses your

42
00:01:44.810 --> 00:01:47.810
phone's camera to read text, find objects, and

43
00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:48.070
more.

44
00:01:48.930 --> 00:01:51.470
This spring, we launched selfie and capture buttons

45
00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:53.810
for Images Mode, which lets users take a

46
00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:56.430
photo with Lookout and hear AI-generated descriptions

47
00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:57.990
of whatever they've photographed.

48
00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:01.250
Like in this example, we've taken a landscape

49
00:02:01.250 --> 00:02:04.110
photo, and Lookout will describe the hills, river,

50
00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:05.630
and hot air balloon in the sky.

51
00:02:07.229 --> 00:02:09.009
In this picture, we can see the hills

52
00:02:09.009 --> 00:02:09.729
and there is a river.

53
00:02:09.970 --> 00:02:11.330
We can see a balloon in the air,

54
00:02:11.370 --> 00:02:12.770
and in the background, we can see the

55
00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:13.590
sky with clouds.

56
00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:17.090
In May, we added Find Mode to Lookout's

57
00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:19.910
set of features, which lets users locate specific

58
00:02:19.910 --> 00:02:22.110
objects by selecting them from a drop-down

59
00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:22.410
list.

60
00:02:22.930 --> 00:02:24.910
We also made improvements to the quality of

61
00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:27.910
Lookout's optical character recognition, which means that the

62
00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:30.530
app can more easily identify text and handwritten

63
00:02:30.530 --> 00:02:32.990
words while it's in Text or Images Mode.

64
00:02:33.670 --> 00:02:35.970
Dear Gabriel, thanks so much for your thoughtful

65
00:02:35.970 --> 00:02:36.330
gift.

66
00:02:36.770 --> 00:02:38.390
It was great seeing you last week.

67
00:02:38.770 --> 00:02:40.190
Hope we can do it again soon.

68
00:02:40.830 --> 00:02:41.930
ZoXo, Aiden.

69
00:02:42.390 --> 00:02:45.370
And we introduced Happiness Tracking Surveys to Lookout

70
00:02:45.370 --> 00:02:47.910
so users can easily share their feedback directly

71
00:02:47.910 --> 00:02:48.530
in the app.

72
00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:50.810
We definitely encourage you to share your thoughts.

73
00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:56.780
Workspace is also an area where we've been

74
00:02:56.780 --> 00:02:59.380
rolling out lots of accessibility features, like in

75
00:02:59.380 --> 00:02:59.780
Google Meet.

76
00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:02.740
Up until recently, one of the common ways

77
00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:04.680
people asked a question in Meet was by

78
00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:07.200
clicking on the hand-raise icon or typing

79
00:03:07.200 --> 00:03:07.920
a keyboard shortcut.

80
00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:10.640
Now, there's a feature in Settings that lets

81
00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:12.360
you raise your physical hand when you want

82
00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:12.760
to speak.

83
00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:15.260
Google Meet will recognize it with gesture detection

84
00:03:15.260 --> 00:03:16.940
and notify all meeting participants.

85
00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:20.220
We also updated our layout options in Google

86
00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:22.300
Meet so users can customize what they see

87
00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:22.980
on their screens.

88
00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:25.420
This option can be great for people who

89
00:03:25.420 --> 00:03:27.920
want to reduce screen clutter and see only

90
00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:30.200
participants with their video feeds shown.

91
00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:33.820
For Google Drive, we're excited to announce that

92
00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:36.920
Drive's web application now supports First Letters Navigation,

93
00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:39.620
a method for quickly finding files and folders.

94
00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:42.860
First Letters Navigation is useful for anyone who

95
00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:45.100
depends on or prefers to use a keyboard,

96
00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:46.720
including screen reader users.

97
00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:49.320
If a user wants to locate a document

98
00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:52.820
they've titled Leadership and Organization, for example, instead

99
00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:55.400
of navigating with arrow keys, they would type

100
00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:57.260
the first letter of the file, in this

101
00:03:57.260 --> 00:03:59.720
case, L, and Drive would jump to the

102
00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:01.280
first item that begins with that letter.

103
00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:06.450
Also, in Drive on web, users can now

104
00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:08.830
update their setting to dark mode, which creates

105
00:04:08.830 --> 00:04:10.810
a darker background with light text.

106
00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:13.310
For some people, this can make visuals clearer

107
00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:14.630
while reducing eyestrain.

108
00:04:16.130 --> 00:04:19.230
In Google Calendar, we're replacing the Appointment Slots

109
00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:22.330
feature with a more accessible and improved Appointments

110
00:04:22.330 --> 00:04:23.230
Schedule option.

111
00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:26.750
With Appointments Schedules, you can create and share

112
00:04:26.750 --> 00:04:28.670
booking pages so people can book time with

113
00:04:28.670 --> 00:04:31.550
you, and you can view booked appointments alongside

114
00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:32.930
your schedule in Google Calendar.

115
00:04:34.230 --> 00:04:36.950
And lastly, since we retired our Gmail HTML

116
00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:39.450
view for desktop and mobile web, we've released

117
00:04:39.450 --> 00:04:41.290
a guide so that screen reader users can

118
00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:43.690
successfully make the switch from HTML to standard

119
00:04:43.690 --> 00:04:43.970
view.

120
00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:45.810
Definitely check it out if you haven't already.

121
00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:52.740
In Google Maps news, we're really excited to

122
00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:55.300
have released Detailed Voice Guidance Worldwide.

123
00:04:56.280 --> 00:04:58.740
Detailed Voice Guidance originally rolled out in 2019,

124
00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:01.640
giving people the ability to receive more guidance

125
00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:03.760
and verbal announcements for walking trips.

126
00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:06.520
Here's a clip of Wakana using the feature

127
00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:08.080
as she navigates the streets of Tokyo.

128
00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:10.740
Detailed Voice Guidance confirms if someone is on

129
00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:13.120
the correct routes, the distance until their next

130
00:05:13.120 --> 00:05:15.640
turn, or if they're approaching a busy intersection.

131
00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:18.280
This feature has been a game-changer for

132
00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:20.840
me personally, especially when on unfamiliar routes.

133
00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:23.620
And it's helpful for anyone who can't easily

134
00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:24.920
look at their phone while walking.

135
00:05:25.460 --> 00:05:27.820
We consider it a virtual curb cut that

136
00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:28.960
benefits many people.

137
00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:31.680
Previously, the feature was only available in English

138
00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:33.840
in the United States and Japanese in Japan.

139
00:05:34.520 --> 00:05:36.880
Now, users anywhere in the world can use

140
00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:39.440
Detailed Voice Guidance in all languages that Maps

141
00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:39.860
supports.

142
00:05:40.900 --> 00:05:43.220
Thanks for tuning in to another episode of

143
00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:44.780
What's New in Google Accessibility.

144
00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:47.140
We hope you've enjoyed learning about some of

145
00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:49.740
our recent efforts to improve our accessibility products

146
00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:50.340
and features.

147
00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:52.720
Be sure to check out our YouTube video

148
00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:55.040
notes, where we've linked to more details about

149
00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:55.940
many of these updates.

150
00:05:56.580 --> 00:05:58.420
If you want to learn more, sign up

151
00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:01.440
for our accessibility newsletter at g.co slash

152
00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:04.800
a11y slash news, or by clicking the link

153
00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:05.880
in the description of this video.

154
00:06:06.460 --> 00:06:07.280
Bye for now!
